WEBVTT

00:04.271 --> 00:06.405
[ car door closes ]

00:06.407 --> 00:10.675
♪♪

00:10.677 --> 00:15.280
After 16 weeks, I'm finally
ready to buy a chair.

00:15.282 --> 00:19.284
There's no rush. I set aside
my whole day for this.

00:19.286 --> 00:22.955
I appreciate you being here.
It's a tough decision.

00:22.957 --> 00:25.490
Wait till
you see inside.

00:25.492 --> 00:27.892
You know I'm not great
at decisions, gene.

00:27.894 --> 00:31.363
And in the past, they've even
caused me to pass out.

00:31.365 --> 00:34.366
How can I help
make this easier for you?

00:34.368 --> 00:39.071
You're a person of integrity,
who likes describing things.

00:40.775 --> 00:44.509
Just give me your honest opinion
about the recliners.

00:44.511 --> 00:47.413
Okay,
I can do that.

00:49.316 --> 00:53.852
Are you ready, america,
to do some sitting?

00:53.854 --> 00:59.658
♪♪

00:59.660 --> 01:01.059
Wow.

01:01.061 --> 01:06.931
♪♪

01:06.933 --> 01:10.469
Hello. My name is joe pera.

01:10.471 --> 01:13.071
And I'm here
helping my friend gene

01:13.073 --> 01:15.474
Decide on
a retirement chair today

01:15.476 --> 01:19.344
So that it can be delivered
before the winter.

01:19.346 --> 01:24.216
With 73 days at or below
freezing in marquette,

01:24.218 --> 01:27.085
We do a lot of sitting here.

01:27.087 --> 01:29.421
I suppose we all do.

01:29.423 --> 01:33.225
I just looked it up, and
the average united states person

01:33.227 --> 01:36.294
Sits 10 to 11 hours a day,

01:36.296 --> 01:40.098
And that doesn't even
include laying down.

01:40.100 --> 01:43.702
Are you sitting right now?

01:43.704 --> 01:46.971
Don't worry, I'm not
going to give bad news.

01:46.973 --> 01:49.974
Just wondering what
you are sitting on.

01:49.976 --> 01:53.779
If it's a chair,
what kind is it?

01:55.315 --> 01:59.551
How would you describe what
it's like to sit on that chair?

02:01.121 --> 02:05.858
I realized today that there are
more types than I ever imagined,

02:05.860 --> 02:10.595
Like that chair over there,
a landmark swivel.

02:10.597 --> 02:12.664
Gene told me that earlier.

02:12.666 --> 02:14.533
He's spent a lot of time
here lately

02:14.535 --> 02:16.869
And was showing me around.

02:16.871 --> 02:19.137
Happy thanksgiving.

02:19.139 --> 02:21.940
The quality of the dining-room
set is top-notch.

02:21.942 --> 02:23.208
Yeah.

02:23.210 --> 02:26.211
You think any of the employees
ever sleep here?

02:26.213 --> 02:28.813
I already asked them,
and they said no.

02:28.815 --> 02:30.014
Oh.

02:30.016 --> 02:31.950
Joe, touch this.

02:31.952 --> 02:34.753
♪♪

02:34.755 --> 02:36.955
Gene, you look like
a lawyer.

02:36.957 --> 02:39.824
I am a lawyer.
I chase ambulances.

02:39.826 --> 02:43.095
I can understand why your
decision is so tough here.

02:43.097 --> 02:44.829
Here, try this one.

02:44.831 --> 02:46.098
Okay.

02:46.100 --> 02:50.235
♪♪

02:52.773 --> 02:54.439
Wow.

02:54.441 --> 02:56.441
Is this a contender?

02:56.443 --> 02:59.177
Nope, just get
your rear-end warmed up.

02:59.179 --> 03:01.714
Hey, gene.
Hi, rhoda.

03:01.716 --> 03:04.182
I brought my friend joe
over to help me out.

03:04.184 --> 03:06.919
Well, hello, joe.
Nice to meet you.

03:06.921 --> 03:08.253
Today the day?

03:08.255 --> 03:09.722
I hope so.

03:09.724 --> 03:12.524
That's the plan.
That's on the agenda.

03:12.526 --> 03:16.328
But to be honest, rhoda,
I really hope so.

03:17.197 --> 03:19.864
Here, I brought you and the gang
some fresh rolls

03:19.866 --> 03:22.467
To eat with your coffee.
Thank you, gene.

03:22.469 --> 03:23.802
I know you know
your way around,

03:23.804 --> 03:26.405
But you let me know
if you have any questions.

03:26.407 --> 03:28.740
I actually have one.

03:28.742 --> 03:32.544
At what point does it go
from sitting to laying down?

03:32.546 --> 03:34.679
Forty-five degrees?

03:34.681 --> 03:36.081
That makes sense.

03:36.083 --> 03:38.951
I always say, when you see
more ceiling than wall.

03:38.953 --> 03:41.353
[ all laugh ]

03:41.355 --> 03:43.288
You see, there's not much more
I can tell you

03:43.290 --> 03:45.223
That gene can
at this point.

03:45.225 --> 03:46.891
I'm around
if you need me.

03:46.893 --> 03:48.293
[ clicks tongue ]
good luck.

03:48.295 --> 03:50.228
Thanks.

03:51.098 --> 03:54.967
Okay, let me show you the chairs
I'm deciding between.

03:54.969 --> 03:58.436
This one's a classic
rocker recliner in black.

03:58.438 --> 04:00.773
Do you like it?
Sure.

04:00.775 --> 04:04.509
Back and forth on the waves,
like a docked boat.

04:04.511 --> 04:05.910
Or a buoy.

04:05.912 --> 04:07.112
Baba booey.

04:07.114 --> 04:10.715
And when you allow yourself
into a state of drowsiness,

04:10.717 --> 04:15.587
You can pull the lever
and go into theater mode.

04:15.589 --> 04:16.989
Wow.

04:16.991 --> 04:20.192
This is an ultra-comfort,
zero-gravity recliner

04:20.194 --> 04:21.794
In whicker,

04:21.796 --> 04:23.595
It's very comfortable,

04:23.597 --> 04:26.598
And it offers a number
of therapeutic positions.

04:26.600 --> 04:28.667
You'll never want to
get out of this one.

04:28.669 --> 04:30.402
That's the problem.

04:30.404 --> 04:34.072
This is an ergonomically-
designed chaise relaxer

04:34.074 --> 04:38.210
Constructed with high-density
polyurethane foam.

04:38.212 --> 04:40.278
It's like it's
from the future.

04:40.280 --> 04:41.746
Yep.

04:41.748 --> 04:44.749
[ sighs ] these are
all great options, gene.

04:44.751 --> 04:47.820
But it seems like
there's more to it than that.

04:47.822 --> 04:50.755
You feel like a different
person in each chair.

04:50.757 --> 04:53.892
Welcome to the universe
of chairs.

04:53.894 --> 04:57.629
It's not as big as the regular
universe, but it's pretty big.

04:57.631 --> 05:00.899
Recliners are just
a tiny little iceberg.

05:00.901 --> 05:03.768
Humans have been sitting
for a while now,

05:03.770 --> 05:07.039
And there are thousands
of years worth of chairs.

05:07.041 --> 05:10.709
It's hard to imagine
previous generations of humans

05:10.711 --> 05:12.845
Sitting like this,
though.

05:12.847 --> 05:15.180
I got a question
for you.

05:15.182 --> 05:19.117
First, let's take a break
and rest our asses.

05:19.119 --> 05:22.287
[ recliner whirs ]

05:30.330 --> 05:33.331
Joe: The question
I wanted to ask was,

05:33.333 --> 05:36.068
Which chair does lulu think
is best?

05:36.070 --> 05:39.538
She said it's my keister
and that she could support me

05:39.540 --> 05:41.806
But she cannot help me.

05:41.808 --> 05:44.342
I think she's lost patience
coming with me to the store.

05:44.344 --> 05:47.880
But we have a good arrangement.
I come here on saturdays.

05:47.882 --> 05:50.949
She has the house to herself
to watch european soccer

05:50.951 --> 05:52.150
In peace.

05:52.152 --> 05:55.019
Lulu's a huge manu fan.

05:55.021 --> 05:58.823
It is nice here. It's like
a large communal living room.

05:58.825 --> 06:02.761
Exactly.
Everyone can sit and talk,

06:02.763 --> 06:05.029
And they don't have to
commit to one chair.

06:05.031 --> 06:07.566
I can't think of a better place
to hang out.

06:07.568 --> 06:08.833
I agree.

06:08.835 --> 06:11.836
However,
if you're retired like me,

06:11.838 --> 06:13.772
You have to
pick a chair.

06:13.774 --> 06:17.642
I need a place to sit
and unpack the last 68 years

06:17.644 --> 06:19.043
While watching
daytime tv.

06:19.045 --> 06:20.245
Mm-hmm.

06:20.247 --> 06:23.315
And if we do it right,
this is the last chair

06:23.317 --> 06:25.584
I'll ever have to buy.

06:25.586 --> 06:27.185
Oh.

06:27.187 --> 06:28.721
[ horn honks ]

06:31.325 --> 06:32.591
[ brakes squeak,
gear clicks ]

06:32.593 --> 06:34.326
Hey, excuse me,

06:34.328 --> 06:36.661
You know how to get to
the mackinaw bridge from here?

06:36.663 --> 06:38.597
No, I'm not sure.

06:38.599 --> 06:41.600
It's okay.
Uh, what are you doing here?

06:41.602 --> 06:45.671
How old are you?
Can you tell me who<i> I</i> am?

06:47.274 --> 06:49.207
Uh...

06:49.209 --> 06:50.675
Don't have a cow, man.

06:50.677 --> 06:52.745
Bart!
Ding, ding, ding!

06:52.747 --> 06:56.481
Hey, remember,
there's no guarantee,

06:56.483 --> 06:59.083
So live life to the fullest.

06:59.085 --> 07:01.787
Can I borrow your cellphone
for a minute?

07:03.023 --> 07:05.024
Sure.

07:08.162 --> 07:10.396
[ camera shutter clicks ]

07:11.565 --> 07:13.432
Positive vibes only.

07:13.434 --> 07:14.833
[ gear clicks ]

07:20.507 --> 07:23.175
[ laughing ]
it was just too strange.

07:23.177 --> 07:25.844
That a friend of yours outside,
gene?

07:25.846 --> 07:29.514
[ laughs ]
I don't know.

07:29.516 --> 07:31.716
So, today's the day?

07:31.718 --> 07:35.053
I was just about to
take my final sits.

07:35.055 --> 07:36.188
Good luck to you.

07:36.190 --> 07:37.690
Thank you.

07:40.461 --> 07:43.261
♪♪

07:43.263 --> 07:46.064
[ indistinct talking ]

07:46.066 --> 07:52.070
♪♪

07:52.072 --> 07:53.806
100%, yes, mm-hmm.

07:53.808 --> 07:56.208
And it comes in
a variety of colors.

07:56.210 --> 07:59.845
[ talking indistinctly ]

08:01.615 --> 08:04.949
[ laughs ]

08:04.951 --> 08:08.120
How does that
chair feel?

08:11.758 --> 08:14.026
Try the buttons.
Try them.

08:14.028 --> 08:15.227
This is gene.

08:15.229 --> 08:19.698
Do you think he could work here
two to three days a week?

08:19.700 --> 08:22.567
[ indistinct talking ]

08:22.569 --> 08:24.837
[ recliner whirs ]

08:24.839 --> 08:26.905
[ man laughs ]

08:28.642 --> 08:31.643
Well...

08:31.645 --> 08:35.514
It's 2018
and the economy's booming,

08:35.516 --> 08:38.650
And he'd be good
with customers.

08:38.652 --> 08:40.119
I agree.

08:42.789 --> 08:44.589
♪♪

08:44.591 --> 08:47.259
How would you like to work
a couple of days a week here?

08:47.261 --> 08:48.993
[ gasps ] oh!
Oh!

08:48.995 --> 08:50.795
Yes,
I would love that!

08:50.797 --> 08:53.666
Joe: We succeeded today
in a big way.

08:53.668 --> 08:56.468
Gene got the part-time position,
and in two weeks,

08:56.470 --> 09:00.138
He is going to order
the ergonomic chaise relaxer

09:00.140 --> 09:03.275
Once eligible
for the employee discount.

09:03.277 --> 09:07.612
And we celebrated with
a drive-thru burger
on the way home.

09:07.614 --> 09:10.683
Hey, it is Saturday night.

09:12.219 --> 09:13.285
Hey, gus.

09:13.287 --> 09:16.955
When I got home,
I automatically went to sit

09:16.957 --> 09:19.491
But realized I had been
doing it all day

09:19.493 --> 09:21.626
So, instead, just walked around

09:21.628 --> 09:24.096
And looked at the chairs
in my house.

09:24.098 --> 09:27.700
I must have sat
in each 5,000 times,

09:27.702 --> 09:33.037
Probably more for some, like
the wingback in my living room.

09:33.039 --> 09:36.174
There are 20 chairs
in my house --

09:36.176 --> 09:40.913
6 dining-room chairs,
4 in my kitchen,

09:40.915 --> 09:44.516
A bedroom chair that I use more
for resting clothes on

09:44.518 --> 09:45.784
Than sitting,

09:45.786 --> 09:47.119
Gus' chair,

09:47.121 --> 09:51.055
In the garage,
4 folding chairs for guests.

09:51.057 --> 09:53.392
My computer chair
is uncomfortable,

09:53.394 --> 09:57.262
But that is good so I won't
play games for too long.

09:57.264 --> 10:00.599
And the chair in my backyard
I should put away

10:00.601 --> 10:02.134
But the leave out during winter

10:02.136 --> 10:05.270
'cause I like to watch
the snow pile on top of it.

10:05.272 --> 10:08.607
This does not even include
my front steps or toilet

10:08.609 --> 10:10.675
Or the chairs
at my nana's house,

10:10.677 --> 10:12.744
Which I still have to sell.

10:12.746 --> 10:16.548
Is 20 chairs a lot of chairs?

10:16.550 --> 10:18.416
Seems like to me,

10:18.418 --> 10:21.553
Considering I have
only one rear-end.

10:21.555 --> 10:25.424
And though I like them,
this is the house I grew up in,

10:25.426 --> 10:28.661
And I chose none of them myself.

10:30.364 --> 10:32.731
Hey.
Hey.

10:34.635 --> 10:37.302
Where do you think
I should sit?

10:39.039 --> 10:40.505
Okay.

10:40.507 --> 10:44.042
I had a hot dog for lunch
and a hamburger for dinner.

10:44.044 --> 10:45.344
[ chuckles ]

10:48.248 --> 10:57.589
♪♪

10:57.591 --> 11:07.332
♪♪

11:07.334 --> 11:12.404
♪♪
